From: Ken Lam <kyip@asia.com>
Source: New Straits Times, 19 Oct 2000 [edited
Hand, Foot and Mouth Disease in Malaysia: Update as of 19 Oct 2000
------------------------------------------------------------------
Since the outbreak of hand, foot and mouth disease (HFMD) in Singapore in
September, the State of Johor at the southern tip of Malaysian Peninsula,
has stepped up its vigilance for this disease. The first fatal case was
reported in Johor on 3 Oct 2000 and the number of HFMD cases has increased
from 36 in the first week of October to 274 in the past week. Other States
which have reported cases are Selangor, Penang, Kedah, Sabah and Terengganu.
In a press release today (New Straits Times, 19 Oct 2000), the HFMD National
Operations Centre stated that as of 18 Oct 2000, 510 patients have been
admitted to hospital in several states and 393 have sought outpatient
treatment.
HFMD is endemic in Malaysia and in 1997, there was a large outbreak which
resulted in the death of over 40 children due to brainstem
encephalomyelitis. The etiological agent was [identified as Enterovirus 71.
Since then, sporadic cases of HFMD caused by Coxsackie A16 virus and
Enterovirus 71 have been reported in the country. On 12 Oct 2000, the first
fatal case resulting from HFMD complication was reported in the University
Hospital Kuala Lumpur. There was a subtle difference between the course of
illness in this case and that in the cases of 1997. The acute progression of
disease in this current case was less aggressive than the cases in 1997.
However the clinical features also suggest brain stem, especially vasomotor
center involvement - tachycardia, transient hypertension, severe
vasoconstriction and LV dysfunction.
Since August 2000, the Department of Medical Microbiology, Universiti Malaya
Medical Centre, has received over 600 samples from 221 suspected HFMD cases,
the majority (206 cases in October) coming from the State of Johor. The
number of hospitals sending samples were Johor (11), Kedah (2), Melaka (1),
Negeri Sembilan (1), Sabah (1), Selangor (2) and the Federal Territory (3).
Coxsackie A16 virus and Enterovirus 71 have been isolated from several cases
of mild HFMD. A different enterovirus was isolated from 2 patients with
severe CNS manifestations and 2 fatal cases seen at [different hospitals.
This isolate stained positive by immunofluorescence using a commercial
pan-enterovirus blend, but did not react with other enterovirus pools, which
included [reagents for detection of Coxsackie A16 virus and Enterovirus 71.
Further identification of this enterovirus by neutralization and molecular
sequencing is in progress.
--
Ken Lam
Consultant Virologist
University Hospital Kuala Lumpur
