From: Dr Muruga Vadivale <vale@pop.jaring.my>
Source: The Straits Times, filed 18 Oct 2000 [edited
<http://straitstimes.asia1.com.sg/asia/mal4_1018.html>

Cause of Outbreak Still Elusive
-------------------------------
KUALA LUMPUR: Health officials in Malaysia suspect a new virus strain to be
the cause of 3 deaths related to hand, foot and mouth disease (HFMD) in
the country last month. To ascertain and isolate the virus which has also
caused an upsurge in the number of HFMD cases in the country, blood samples
from the 3 victims have been sent to the Princess Margaret Hospital in
Perth, Australia, for tests. Universiti Malaya Medical Centre (UMMC)
microbiologist Dr Chua Kaw Bing left for Perth over the weekend for
consultations and to conduct tests with experts there.
He revealed last week that the enterovirus extracted by the UMMC team so far
seemed to be related to one known as Enterovirus type 71, which was found to
have been responsible for the HFMD-related outbreak in Sarawak in 1997 which
killed more than 30 children. In the Sarawak case, a series of sudden infant
deaths occurred against a background of a large outbreak of HFMD in the
state. The deaths were suspected [initially to have been caused by a rare
strain of Coxsackie virus, [because most of the victims had a history of
HFMD, but died of acute heart failure. But after calling in foreign experts,
including those from Atlanta's Centers for Disease Control, authorities were
able to identify the Enterovirus 71 as the cause of that epidemic.
Health Ministry Disease Control Division principal assistant director Dr
Devan Kurup had said earlier that Enterovirus 71 was suspected to be the
cause this time. But officials are now looking at the possibility of a new
strain as well.
[Byline: Leslie Lau
