Date: Thu, 19 Oct 2000 21:34:49 +0800
From: Dr Muruga Vadivale <vale@pop.jaring.my>
Source: The Straits Times, filed 19 Oct 2000 [edited
<http://straitstimes.asia1.com.sg/primenews/pri7_1019.html>

Enterovirus 71 from Malaysia & Singapore distinct from Taiwan virus
-------------------------------------------------------------------
SINGAPORE: Scientists have shortened the time it takes to test for viruses
which may cause hand, foot and mouth disease (HFMD). Currently, it takes
anywhere from 2 to 3 weeks from the time the symptoms are noticed to
confirming the viruses responsible. The National University of Singapore
researchers have found a way to cut the time needed to just 2 to 3 days, and
are working on getting the detective work done on the same day.
The recent virus scare saw more than 1725 people infected with the mild but
contagious disease. The Department of Microbiology's Enterovirus 71 Research
Team has been looking into tests for the viruses, called enteroviruses, for
more than 2 years. [Infection with these viruses may [produce symptoms
seen in illnesses like the [common cold and HFMD. Some may cause
inflammation of the heart and brain.
The NUS team, which had help from Singapore General Hospital, tested for the
virus by applying a molecular typing process, which analyses the molecular
structure of the virus. By doing so, the virus could be diagnosed more
quickly. Associate Professor Poh Chit Laa, the team's principal
investigator, said it had been able to directly isolate the virus. Prof Poh
said while the Enterovirus 71 strains isolated in Singapore and Malaysia
were similar, they were different from one [previously isolatedin Taiwan.
[Byline: Sharmilpal Kaur
--
Dr M.Vadivale
<vale@pop.jaring.my>
[The first of these 3 reports is the most informative and precise. The
accumulating evidence indicates that Enterovirus type 71 infection is a
major factor in the concurrent epidemics of HFMD in Malaysia and Singapore.
However, there is now evidence that in Malaysia another, as yet
unidentified, enterovirus may be associated with the more severe forms of
the disease. HFMD has been considered a rather benign infection of
childhood, but since 1974 there have been several outbreaks in South East
and East Asia which have been accompanied by some deaths. Following the
outbreak in Malaysia in 1997 in which 28 children died, a well-organised
clinical surveillance system was established in Taiwan on the initiative of
Professor Monto Ho (see Ho et al., N.Engl. J.Med. 1999, 341, 929-935). This
surveillance system was in place in time to follow the course of the
largest recorded HFMD epidemic which may have affected as many as 1 484 000
people with 78 deaths in Taiwan during 1998. Among patients from whom a
virus was isolated, Enterovirus 71 was isolated from 49% of outpatients
with uncomplicated HFMD, from 75% of hospitalised patients who survived,
and from 92% of patients who died. Most of those who died were young (5
years of age or less) and the majority died of pulmonary edema and
pulmonary hemorrhage. However, although Enterovirus 71 appeared to be
associated with the most severe disease, other viruses were present.
Virological analysis of the current outbreak in Malaysia and Singapore may
help to clarify the relative roles of different enteroviruses in the
manifestation of HFMD. - Mod.CP
